---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";

const frontmatter = {
  title: "Editorial Standards",
  description:
    "How PatientGuide.io creates, reviews, and maintains medical information.",
};
---

<Layout frontmatter={frontmatter}>
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>Editorial Standards</h1>

    <h2>What PatientGuide.io is</h2>
    <p>
      PatientGuide.io is an educational health information site. We explain
      medical concepts in plain language, with an emphasis on clarity,
      uncertainty, and practical interpretation â€” not medical directives.
    </p>

    <h2>What we publish</h2>
    <p>We publish:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Guides that explain conditions, tests, treatments, and health concepts</li>
      <li>Hubs that organize guides into coherent learning paths</li>
      <li>Posts that explore concepts, evidence interpretation, and health literacy topics</li>
    </ul>

    <p>We avoid:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Personalized medical advice</li>
      <li>"Miracle cure" claims</li>
      <li>Alarmist framing</li>
      <li>Content designed to drive clicks rather than understanding</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How we write</h2>
    <p>Our default style is:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Clear, structured, and conservative</li>
      <li>Transparent about what is known vs uncertain</li>
      <li>Focused on what patients typically need to understand to have better conversations with clinicians</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      When clinical decisions depend on individual context (age, pregnancy,
      comorbidities, medications, or risk factors), we explicitly say so.
    </p>

    <h2>Evidence standards</h2>
    <p>We prioritize evidence in roughly this order:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>High-quality clinical guidelines and consensus statements</li>
      <li>Systematic reviews and meta-analyses</li>
      <li>Randomized controlled trials (where applicable)</li>
      <li>Large observational studies (with careful interpretation)</li>
      <li>Mechanistic or early-stage research (clearly labeled as preliminary)</li>
    </ol>

    <p>We try to state:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>What the evidence shows</li>
      <li>How strong the evidence is</li>
      <li>What remains uncertain or debated</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Medical review and updates</h2>
    <p>
      We aim to keep pages current. Some pages may be updated more frequently
      than others, especially when guidance changes or major new research
      appears.
    </p>

    <p>When a page is reviewed or updated, we may indicate:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Publish date</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Updated date</strong> (when changes are meaningful)</li>
      <li><strong>Last reviewed</strong> (editorial review without major changes)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Conflicts of interest and funding</h2>
    <p>
      If we ever publish sponsored content or have financial relationships
      relevant to a topic, we will disclose them clearly on the page.
    </p>

    <h2>Corrections policy</h2>
    <p>If you believe something is incorrect, unclear, or misleading:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>We take that seriously.</li>
      <li>We will review the issue and update the page if needed.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>
      Feedback and corrections can be sent to the site contact address listed on
      the <a href="/contact">Contact page</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Layout>
